2026-05-22 | Search in Rotated Sorted Array

	Question
Return index of target, or -1 if absent.
	Key Insight
In a rotated sorted array:
		one half is always sorted.
Using binary search:
- identify sorted half  
- check whether target lies there  
- discard the other half
	Approach
1.	Initialize:
		left = 0
		right = n-1
2.	While left <= right:
		find mid
3.	If nums[mid] == target:
		return mid
4.	Check which half is sorted:
		If left half sorted:
				nums[left] <= nums[mid]
		Else:
				right half sorted
5.	Decide where target belongs
		and shrink search space
6.	If not found:
		return -1
	Time Complexity
	O(log n)
	Space Complexity
	O(1)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int search(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = nums.size() - 1;
        while(left <= right){
            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
            if(nums[mid] == target)
                return mid;
            // left half sorted
            if(nums[left] <= nums[mid]){
                if(target >= nums[left] &&
                   target < nums[mid]){
                    right = mid - 1;
                }
                else{
                    left = mid + 1;
                }
            }
            // right half sorted
            else{
                if(target > nums[mid] &&
                   target <= nums[right]){
                    left = mid + 1;
                }
                else{
                    right = mid - 1;
                }
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Even after rotation:
		at least one half remains sorted.  
Binary search uses this property
to eliminate half the search space each time.
